{"questionId":"9066655","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">This question is about a mug made of a lead alloy.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/6824f4585e40a884f8d6d709dd0741342bbc8407.png\" width=\"169\" height=\"190\"></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">The rate of lead dissolving in common beverages with various pH values was analysed.</span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/df3f6745b36ab97778d6d32949a1715917317f1f.png\" width=\"648\" height=\"457\"></span></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">A mean daily lead intake of greater than 5.0 × 10<sup>−6</sup> g per kg of body weight results in increased lead levels in the body.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Calculate the volume, in dm<sup>3</sup>, of tap water from experiment 8 which would exceed this daily lead intake for an 80.0 kg man.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">«daily limit = 5.0&nbsp;× 10<sup>–6</sup> g kg<sup>–1</sup> × 80.0 kg =» 4.0 × 10<sup>–4</sup> «g of lead»&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">«volume <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" = \\frac{{4.0 \\times {{10}^{ - 4}}{\\text{ g}}}}{{1.5 \\times {{10}^{ - 2}}{\\text{g d}}{{\\text{m}}^{ - 3}}}} = \">\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>4.0</mn>\n      <mo>×</mo>\n      <mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mrow>\n            <mn>10</mn>\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow>\n            <mo>−</mo>\n            <mn>4</mn>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n      </mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>&nbsp;g</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>1.5</mn>\n      <mo>×</mo>\n      <mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mrow>\n            <mn>10</mn>\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow>\n            <mo>−</mo>\n            <mn>2</mn>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n      </mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>g d</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mrow>\n            <mtext>m</mtext>\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow>\n            <mo>−</mo>\n            <mn>3</mn>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n</math></span>» 2.7 × 10<sup>–2</sup>/0.027 «dm<sup>3</sup>»&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><strong>Note: </strong>Award <strong>[2]</strong> for correct final answer</span></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9066655","referenceCode":"19M.3.hl.TZ2.c(ii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"A mean daily lead intake of greater than 5.0 × 10−6 g per kg of body weight results in increased lead levels in the body. Calculate the volume, in dm3, of tap water from experiment","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 1: Stoichiometric relationships","1.3 Reacting masses and volumes","Core","Topic 1: Stoichiometric relationships"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}